    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What if I finish my task before the 25 minutes are up?</summary>
        <p>If you complete your task before the pomodoro ends, use the remaining time for "overlearning" — review your work, refine it, make small improvements, or start planning your next task. The key is to use the full interval productively rather than cutting it short, which helps build the habit of sustained focus and often leads to unexpected improvements in your work.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can I use longer or shorter intervals instead of 25 minutes?</summary>
        <p>Yes, many practitioners adapt the interval length to suit their work. Some people use 50-minute intervals with 10-minute breaks for deep creative work, while others prefer 15-minute intervals for tasks that require frequent context switching. The standard 25/5 ratio is a well-tested starting point, but feel free to experiment once you are comfortable with the basic technique.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I handle interruptions during a pomodoro?</summary>
        <p>For internal interruptions (your own thoughts and urges), write them down on a piece of paper and return to your task — this is called the "inform, negotiate, call back" strategy. For external interruptions from colleagues or phone calls, politely let them know you are in the middle of something and will get back to them in a few minutes. If the interruption is truly urgent and cannot wait, void the pomodoro, handle the interruption, and start a fresh one.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is the Pomodoro Technique good for studying?</summary>
        <p>The Pomodoro Technique is excellent for studying. The regular breaks prevent mental fatigue, and the structured intervals help students avoid marathon study sessions that lead to diminishing returns. Research shows that spaced repetition and focused intervals improve memory retention. Many students find they learn more in four focused pomodoros than in several hours of unfocused studying.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How many pomodoros should I aim for in a day?</summary>
        <p>Most practitioners find that 8 to 12 pomodoros per workday is a productive and sustainable range, representing roughly 3.5 to 5 hours of deeply focused work. This may sound low, but remember that these are intervals of genuine, uninterrupted concentration. The rest of the workday is naturally consumed by meetings, emails, breaks, and other activities. Track your pomodoros for a week to establish your personal baseline.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

